Author: Mylo#8306
Content:
@dukeleto  gotta ask for your git foo on getting number of contributors to  a particular repo - or dbl check at least what github has.
i have a discrepancy between the github contributor count vs what comes up in `git log -s -n | wc -l` or `git log -s -n --no-merges | wc -l`
these outputs are `547` & `542` respectively on jl777/komodo (branch master)

But github lists 424 contributors to the project.

Any ideas how gh comes up with this figure?

Author: Mylo#8306
Content:
This i found a reason:
```
If the email address you used to author the commits has not been added to your GitHub account, your commits won't be linked to your account, and you won't appear in the contributors graph. 
```

Author: dukeleto#7326
Content: @Mylo yes, github merges multiple emails into Github users/contributors, if it can

Author: dukeleto#7326
Content: those stats will never line up perfectly

Author: dukeleto#7326
Content: @Mylo at fancy companies, you can have 456 commits that say `fuck` as the commit message, but when you submit to the "official" company repo, usually it's rebased into 1 commit with a meaningful message. And I have worked at places that *forbade* any type of code comments

Author: dukeleto#7326
Content: so for blackjoker, it would mean doing a `git squash` before sending a PR, to keep history "pretty"

Author: dukeleto#7326
Content: There are 2 very very very different camps of Git Users: Historians and Story-Tellers

Author: dukeleto#7326
Content: Are you a Historian or a Story-Teller?

Author: dukeleto#7326
Content: Historians want every single shitty commit from history, no data must be lost!!!! Story-Tellers want a nice story to be told with commits

Author: dukeleto#7326
Content: it's like emacs vs vi

Author: dukeleto#7326
Content: Their logic was that code should be "intention-revealing" and if you need to write a comment, you should name your variables and functions better. Additionally, since tests were required, those were kind of the "contract" or "code documentation" for how the code was expected to work

Author: dukeleto#7326
Content: It's an extreme position

Author: jl777c#5810
Content: the superiority of the historical commit is proven simply by the ability to binary search the set of commits to isolate what change introduced a bug. a single squashed commit loses all that and makes it nearly impossible to find out what change introduced a bug

Author: jl777c#5810
Content: this is not a style issue, but more a better way to debug

Author: jl777c#5810
Content: if you know the bug was introduced with some specific 10 line change, that is orders of magnitude easier than finding out it is buried some where in thousands of commits with tens of thousands of lines
